# Pancakes & Booze — host routing (Cloudflare Pages syntax)
#
# Host processes this file at deploy time. Rules evaluate top-to-bottom; the
# FIRST matching rule wins. Put specific rules BEFORE catchalls.
#
# Status codes:
#   200 = rewrite (URL stays in browser, server serves a different file)
#   301 = permanent redirect (browser URL changes, search engines update)
#
# ─── Cloudflare Pages gotchas (the two weird ones that bit us) ───────────
#
# 1. Catch-all `/:slug` patterns DON'T skip real static files at the root.
#    Cloudflare's docs claim static assets win over _redirects, but in practice
#    a root-level `/:slug /city 200` rule catches /logo.png, /shows.json,
#    /favicon.ico, etc. and serves city.html for them. This broke our launch
#    (CITY NOT FOUND everywhere, missing logo, empty shows list) because the
#    browser was getting HTML when it asked for those binary/JSON files.
#
#    Fix: list every city slug EXPLICITLY below instead of using `/:slug`.
#    When a new city launches, add its slug here (and to the Shows sheet).
#
# 2. Cloudflare Pages auto-301-redirects `.html` URL paths to the extensionless
#    version ("pretty URLs", not disableable on the free tier). If we rewrite
#    /austin → /city.html, Pages 301s to /city, which would re-match any
#    catch-all → infinite loop. Dropping .html from the rewrite destination
#    (just `/city`) sidesteps this — Pages still finds city.html via the
#    pretty-URL resolution in the OTHER direction.

# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
